            <biogHist>
                <p>William MacLeod Thorburn was born in Duirinish, Inverness-shire, the son of John
                    Thorburn, crofter, and Catherine Thorburn n√©e MacLean. By the time of the 1861
                    census, he had settled in Dundee and was working as an apprentice grocer; in
                    1871 he is described as a 'grocer and wine merchant - master' and on 21 March of
                    the same year he married Agnes Whitelaw Walton. By the time of the 1891 census
                    they had six children: William (19), Agnes (11), John (9), Lauchlin (5),
                    Willimina (3) and Walton (10 months). In later life, William Thorburn became a
                    Free Church missionary and is recorded as being at the Free Church Manse in
                    Carnoch, Contin in the 1911 census, although at this time no other family
                    members are mentioned.</p>
                <p>He died in 1918 in the Free Church Manse in Dores, Inverness-shire of a
                    perforating gastric ulcer and peritonitis; his son Lauchlin was the
                    informant.</p>
                <p>Carmichael collected a poem from William entitled 'Am fac thu each seachad an
                    seo?' for the safeguarding of animals. </p>
